    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-12-05T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-12-05T10:00:00-05:00" n="797"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d797">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760i.61/147: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Estonia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_WJC1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wiley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tallinn</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-12-05T17:00:00+02:00"
                            >December 5, 1939—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 5—2 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>141. There has been an epidemic of rumors alleging new Soviet demands on Estonia
                    including disbanding of civil guard. I am authoritatively told at the Foreign
                    Office that these reports are false and that no new demands of any kind have
                    been presented. It was made clear though that Foreign Office regards the
                    situation with anxiety and fears that Soviet pressure may be applied in a
                    dangerous manner particularly during present visit of General <persName
                        corresp="#p_LJ1">Laidoner</persName>, Commander in Chief, to Moscow. (I
                    think recognition of Terijoki government<note n="67" xml:id="d797fn67">The
                        puppet, Communist Soviet government of the “Democratic Republic of Finland”,
                        set up on December 1, 1939, in the town of Terijoki under the nominal
                        leadership of <persName corresp="#p_KOW1">Otto Kuusinen</persName>.</note>
                    is regarded as chief danger point).</p>
                <pb facs="1086" n="980" xml:id="pg_980"/>
                <p>Economic relations with the Soviet Union seem to be following happy course.
                    Former is paying in dollars both for garrison expenses and Estonian exports to
                    Soviet Union. Estonia has been permitted to make payments for Soviet exports
                    from blocked rouble accounts. According to Foreign Office negotiations for
                    export of Estonian dairy products to Soviet Union concluded at satisfactory
                    price level.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wiley</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
